#
# arkouda_server is Arkouda's BACKEND — a Chapel
# parallel program that mimics NumPy's ndarray
# semantics at HPC scale.  Driven from a Python
# client (the `arkouda` Python package) that
# sends commands over ZeroMQ to this server.
# Arkouda's design: Python REPL for ergonomics +
# Chapel server for distributed parallel
# performance.  Authored by Bears-R-Us (US DoD-
# affiliated research lab).  280 GH stars.
# Sister tools: arkouda Python client (in PyPI),
# chpl (Chapel compiler — in corpus as `_chpl`),
# zmq tools (ZeroMQ underlies the client/server
# RPC).
#
# Critical extraction note: arkouda_server uses
# **Chapel `config const`/`config var`/`config
# param` language-level CLI mechanism** at
# ServerConfig.chpl:55+ et seq — corpus's **first
# documented Chapel CLI mechanism**.  Chapel's
# `config` KEYWORD is a LANGUAGE-LEVEL FEATURE,
# not a library.  Any module-scope declaration
# qualified with `config` becomes a CLI FLAG
# auto-generated by the Chapel compiler.  The
# compiler walks the AST for `config` declarations
# and emits a parser at compile time.  Distinct
# from EVERY OTHER CLI LIBRARY in the corpus —
# no library, no spec table, no parser
# construction.  Closest analog: R287 Nim
# parseopt (token iterator at language level) but
# Nim parseopt is still a stdlib module that the
# caller invokes.  Chapel is the ONLY language in
# the corpus where the CLI mechanism is
# COMPILER-PROVIDED with ZERO USER CODE required.
# Extends cross-language CLI taxonomy to FIFTY-
# NINE library variants: Rust (6), Go (4),
# Python (3), Crystal 1 OptionParser (R269),
# Haskell (R270), OCaml (R271), C (R272),
# Java (R276), Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278),
# Dart (R279), Ruby (R280), Perl (R281),
# PHP (R282), Swift (R283), F# (R284), Lua (R285),
# C# (R286), Nim 1 parseopt (R287), Zig (R288),
# D (R289), Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294),
# Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296),
# SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300),
# Nim 2 cligen (R301), Clojure 1 babashka.cli
# (R302), Gleam Glint (R303), Ada GNAT.Command_
# Line (R304), C++ 1 CLI11 (R305), Elixir Optimus
# (R306), Vala GLib.OptionContext (R307), Hare
# stdlib getopt (R308), Standard ML stdlib GetOpt
# (R309), Fortran M_CLI2 (R310), Guile (ice-9
# getopt-long) (R311), Free Pascal TCustomApplication
# (R312), Idris 2 System.GetOpts (R313), Mercury
# stdlib getopt_io (R314), Eiffel Gobo AP_PARSER
# (R315), C++ 2 boost::program_options (R316),
# Forth/Gforth `next-arg` (R317), Clojure 2
# org.clojure/tools.cli (R318), Roc weaver (R319),
# **Chapel `config` keyword** (R320 — NEW).
# **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 59 cross-language
# CLI library variants documented.  Chapel joins
# the taxonomy as one of only TWO documented
# LANGUAGE-LEVEL CLI mechanisms (alongside R317
# Forth's "language-as-library" — but Forth has
# no auto-parsing; Chapel does).
#
# Critical extraction note: arkouda_server uses
# **Chapel `config const`/`config var`/`config
# param` declaration-as-flag pattern** at
# ServerConfig.chpl:55-110 et seq — `config const
# NAME = VALUE` auto-exposes the binding as a
# CLI FLAG.  Three variants:
#   `config const NAME = VALUE`    immutable flag
#                                  (runtime-set,
#                                  unchangeable
#                                  after init)
#   `config var NAME = VALUE`      mutable flag
#                                  (runtime-set,
#                                  reassignable)
#   `config param NAME = VALUE`    compile-time
#                                  parameter (set
#                                  via `-sNAME=VAL`
#                                  to chpl
#                                  compiler)
# Type INFERRED from initializer or DECLARED via
# `: TYPE` annotation.  Distinct from R272 C
# POSIX getopt (caller writes option string), R301
# Nim cligen (proc-signature), R310 Fortran
# M_CLI2 (single-string-packed spec).  Chapel's
# approach: DECLARATION-AS-FLAG — corpus's
# **first documented declaration-as-flag CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: arkouda_server uses
# **Chapel enum-variant-auto-match CLI flag
# values** at ServerConfig.chpl:65-66 — `config
# var logLevel = LogLevel.INFO;` accepts both
# `--logLevel=LogLevel.DEBUG` (FULL qualified
# name) and `--logLevel=DEBUG` (Chapel resolves
# the SHORT form).  Sister to R295 CL clingon
# `:option-type :choice :choices`, R304 Ada
# `Define_Alias` for enum aliases.  Chapel's
# approach: ENUM-VARIANT-AUTO-MATCH — corpus's
# **first documented enum-variant-auto-match CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: arkouda_server uses
# **Chapel `private config` module-scoped
# disambiguation** at arkouda_server.chpl:12 —
# `private config const logLevel = ServerConfig.
# logLevel;` scopes the config to the current
# module.  When the same config NAME exists in
# multiple modules, the user must DISAMBIGUATE
# with `--ModuleName.NAME=VALUE` qualified syntax.
# E.g. `--ServerConfig.logLevel=DEBUG` vs `--logLevel=DEBUG`
# in some other module.  Distinct from EVERY
# other CLI library — corpus's **first documented
# qualified-module-prefix-for-disambiguation CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: arkouda_server uses
# **Chapel `try! getEnv(NAME, DEFAULT)` env-var
# fallback in config initializer** at
# ServerConfig.chpl:110 — `config const
# serverConnectionInfo: string = try!
# getEnv("ARKOUDA_SERVER_CONNECTION_INFO", "");`.
# Chapel's `try!` is non-recoverable error
# propagation (panics on failure); `getEnv` reads
# OS env vars.  The pattern: CONFIG DEFAULT is
# RESOLVED AT RUNTIME via an arbitrary Chapel
# expression that can include env-var reads.
# Distinct from R272 C POSIX getopt (no env-var
# integration), R313 Idris 2 (no built-in env
# support).  Chapel's approach: USER-CODE ENV-VAR
# FALLBACK as a `getEnv` call in the initial
# expression — corpus's **first documented env-
# var-as-config-default CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: arkouda_server uses
# **Chapel compiler AUTO-GENERATES CLI parser
# from AST walk** at compile time — the Chapel
# compiler walks every module's AST looking for
# `config` declarations, then EMITS a parser
# that reads argv and INITIALIZES each config
# variable from its corresponding CLI flag.  No
# user code participates in CLI parsing.  No
# `parse()` call, no `main()` argument
# unpacking, no spec table.  Distinct from EVERY
# OTHER CLI MECHANISM in the corpus — Chapel's
# approach is COMPILER-PROVIDED ZERO-USER-CODE
# CLI PARSING.  Closest analog: R287 Nim parseopt
# (still requires user `for kind, key, val in
# getopt():` loop), R317 Forth/Gforth `next-arg`
# (still requires user matching).  Chapel is
# truly UNIQUE: ZERO USER CODE for CLI handling.
# Corpus's **first documented compiler-walks-
# AST-for-config CLI mechanism**.
#
